UPDATE articles 
SET content = '{"en":"{\"en\":\"{\\\"en\\\":\\\"{\\\\\\\"en\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\"{\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"en\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"{\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"en\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<p><strong>Quick answer:</strong> In Turkey, a pharmacy is called an “eczane” (usually marked with a red E sign). Most pharmacies keep standard daytime hours that can vary by province, and outside normal hours there’s a rotating “on-duty” pharmacy system (nöbetçi eczane) so you can still get medicines at night and on Sundays. In an emergency, call 112.</p>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<p>This guide is written for UK travellers and focuses on calm, practical steps — no panic, no scare stories.</p>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<h2>1) What UK travellers should know about Turkish pharmacies (the basics)</h2>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<p>Turkey’s pharmacy experience is generally straightforward:</p>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<ul>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>Pharmacies are professional, regulated settings (not a general convenience store).</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>Many pharmacists are used to helping visitors, especially in tourist areas and big cities.</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>You can often get help with common issues (cold symptoms, allergies, sun care, stomach upsets) — but some medicines are prescription-only under Turkish rules.</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>A UK prescription isn’t accepted as a prescription in Turkish pharmacies; if a medicine needs a prescription in Turkey, you’ll need a Turkish prescription.</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n</ul>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<p><strong>Simple rule:</strong> Treat the pharmacy as your first “calm help point” for non-urgent issues — and treat 112 as the emergency route.</p>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<p>Internal guide if you want it later:\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<a href=\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"/guide/emergency-numbers-pharmacies-getting-help-turkey-guide\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\">Emergency Numbers & Getting Help in Turkey</a>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<a href=\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"/guide/travel-insurance-turkey-uk-guide\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\">Travel Insurance for Turkey from the UK</a>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<h2>2) Recognising a pharmacy: “Eczane” and the red “E”</h2>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<p>In most places you’ll spot a pharmacy quickly:</p>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<ul>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>“Eczane” on the sign</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>Red E symbol</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n</ul>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<p><strong>UK-friendly tip:</strong> If you’re searching on your phone, try keywords like:</p>\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<ul>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>“eczane near me”</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>“nöbetçi eczane” + your district (for night/Sunday)</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n</ul>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<h2>3) Opening hours: what to expect (and why it varies)</h2>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<p>Pharmacy hours can differ by city and province. As a practical reference, Istanbul’s pharmacists’ chamber has published pharmacy working hours as 09:00–19:00 (weekday and Saturday in that notice).</p>\n<figure class=\"my-8\">\n<img src=\"/images/articles/pharmacist-helping-customer-counter-1767987110935.jpg\" alt=\"{\"en\":\"Pharmacies in Turkey for UK Travellers: How to Get Common Medicines (Simple, Calm Guide)\",\"tr\":\"Türkiye''de Eczaneler ve İlaç Temini (TR Pasif)\"} - Image 2\" class=\"w-full h-auto rounded-xl shadow-lg\" loading=\"lazy\" onError=\"this.onerror=null;this.src=''/images/articles/turkey_holiday_generic_1767986408887.jpg'';\" />\n</figure>\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<p><strong>Common travel reality:</strong>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<ul>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>Many pharmacies are open during the day</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>On Sundays and late evenings, most standard pharmacies are closed except on-duty pharmacies</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n</ul>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<p><strong>Simple rule:</strong> After hours, don’t hunt randomly — search for the on-duty pharmacy.</p>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<h2>4) The on-duty system: “Nöbetçi Eczane” (how night/Sunday access works)</h2>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<p>Turkey uses a rotating duty system so there is always at least one open pharmacy for each area at night and on Sundays.</p>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<p><strong>How it works in practice:</strong>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<ul>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>Your nearest closed pharmacy often posts the address of the on-duty pharmacy.</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>You can also find on-duty lists online via local pharmacists’ chambers.</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n</ul>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<p>Example (official local chamber): Istanbul Eczacı Odası provides an up-to-date “Nöbetçi Eczaneler” page for Istanbul/Yalova. They also describe their on-duty pharmacy app and how it helps you find the nearest option.</p>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<p><strong>UK-friendly tip:</strong> If you’re in Istanbul and it’s late, use the chamber list first. It saves time and keeps things calm.</p>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<h2>5) What you can usually get at a pharmacy (tourist-friendly overview)</h2>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<p>This section is intentionally general — because specific medicines vary by brand and local regulation.</p>\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<p><strong>Often handled well at pharmacies:</strong>\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<ul>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>Basic symptom relief products (colds, cough, sore throat comfort)</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>Allergy support products</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>Sunburn support and skin comfort products</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>Rehydration / electrolyte support products</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>Simple first-aid items (plasters, antiseptic basics)</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n</ul>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<p><strong>What often requires extra steps:</strong>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<ul>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>Medicines that are prescription-only in Turkey (you’ll need a Turkish prescription)</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>Anything classed as “strong” or controlled</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n</ul>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<p><strong>Important:</strong> The UK Foreign Office notes that legal status and regulation of medicines can differ between the UK and other countries, and that British prescriptions are not accepted in Turkey.</p>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<p><strong>Simple rule:</strong> If it’s “strong” in the UK, assume it might require a Turkish prescription and ask calmly.</p>\n<figure class=\"my-8\">\n<img src=\"/images/articles/medicine-shelf-sunscreen-vitamins-1767987110935.jpg\" alt=\"{\"en\":\"Pharmacies in Turkey for UK Travellers: How to Get Common Medicines (Simple, Calm Guide)\",\"tr\":\"Türkiye''de Eczaneler ve İlaç Temini (TR Pasif)\"} - Image 3\" class=\"w-full h-auto rounded-xl shadow-lg\" loading=\"lazy\" onError=\"this.onerror=null;this.src=''/images/articles/turkey_holiday_generic_1767986408887.jpg'';\" />\n</figure>\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<h2>6) Antibiotics and prescriptions: don’t assume</h2>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<p>A key example: antibiotics are regulated and are not generally sold as over-the-counter items in Turkey; pharmacies are not allowed to dispense them without a doctor’s prescription.</p>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<p><strong>UK-friendly tip:</strong> If you think you need something prescription-based, skip the guessing and ask the pharmacy:\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n“Does this require a prescription here?”\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\nIf yes, ask:\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n“What’s the simplest way to get a Turkish prescription?”</p>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<h2>7) If you brought medication from the UK: how to travel smarter</h2>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<p>If you take regular medication, travel-health guidance commonly recommends carrying evidence it’s prescribed to you, such as a copy of your prescription and/or a doctor’s letter.</p>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<p>A Turkish consulate info note also advises travellers to carry a medical report/prescription detailing purpose and dosage when travelling with medications.</p>\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<p><strong>Simple rule:</strong> Keep medicines in original packaging + keep proof (digital + paper if possible). It reduces stress.</p>\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<h2>8) The easiest “how-to” when you feel unwell (calm, practical steps)</h2>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<h3>Step 1: Decide if it’s urgent</h3>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<ul>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>If it’s an emergency or you need urgent help: <strong>call 112</strong>.</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>If it’s non-urgent and you need advice/products: go to an eczane.</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n</ul>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<h3>Step 2: If it’s after hours</h3>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<p>Search for:\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n“nöbetçi eczane” + your area/district\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\nOr use local chamber lists (example: Istanbul).</p>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<h3>Step 3: Bring the right info (this makes it fast)</h3>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<ul>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>A short note of symptoms (1–2 lines)</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>Allergies</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>Current medications (photo of labels helps)</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>If relevant: your insurance details (not always needed for a pharmacy purchase, but useful overall)</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n</ul>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<p><strong>UK-friendly tip:</strong> The pharmacist can help best when you describe the problem, not when you insist on a specific brand.</p>\n<figure class=\"my-8\">\n<img src=\"/images/articles/travel-first-aid-kit-contents-1767987110935.jpg\" alt=\"{\"en\":\"Pharmacies in Turkey for UK Travellers: How to Get Common Medicines (Simple, Calm Guide)\",\"tr\":\"Türkiye''de Eczaneler ve İlaç Temini (TR Pasif)\"} - Image 4\" class=\"w-full h-auto rounded-xl shadow-lg\" loading=\"lazy\" onError=\"this.onerror=null;this.src=''/images/articles/turkey_holiday_generic_1767986408887.jpg'';\" />\n</figure>\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<h2>9) How to communicate at the pharmacy (without perfect Turkish)</h2>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<p>You can do this in simple English. Keep it short and practical.</p>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<p><strong>Copy-paste phrases (save in Notes)</strong>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<ul>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>“Hello — I’m visiting from the UK. Could you help me?”</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>“I have these symptoms: ______.”</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>“Do I need a prescription for this in Turkey?”</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>“Is there a non-prescription option for symptom relief?”</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>“I’m allergic to ______.”</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>“Can you write down the name of the product and how to use it?”</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>“Do you have an English leaflet / instructions?”</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n</ul>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<p><strong>Simple rule:</strong> Ask them to write it down. That prevents misunderstandings.</p>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<h2>10) Paying, receipts, and insurance (keep it organised)</h2>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<p>Most travellers just want a smooth purchase:</p>\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<ul>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>Pay normally (card or cash depending on the location)</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>Ask for a receipt if you’re keeping records or may claim later</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n</ul>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<p><strong>UK-friendly tip:</strong> If you think you may claim something through insurance, keep:\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n- the receipt\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n- a short note of what it was for\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n- any medical documentation if you had a clinic visit</p>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<p>Related: <a href=\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"/guide/travel-insurance-turkey-uk-guide\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\">Travel Insurance for Turkey from the UK: What to Check</a>\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<h2>11) Where pharmacies help the most: the “holiday disruptors”</h2>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<p>These are the issues that most commonly ruin a day — and where quick pharmacy support can help you get back to enjoying Turkey:</p>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<ul>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>Sun overexposure and skin discomfort</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>Mild stomach upset from heat, schedule changes, or new foods</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>Seasonal allergies</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>Blisters from walking more than you do at home</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>Simple colds from air-con changes</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n</ul>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<p><strong>Simple rule:</strong> Fix the small problem early so it doesn’t become a two-day problem.</p>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<h2>12) Your “Pharmacy Plan” for day 1 (this makes you feel confident)</h2>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<p>Before you travel (or on arrival), do this once:</p>\n<figure class=\"my-8\">\n<img src=\"/images/articles/prescription-paper-doctor-hand-1767987110935.jpg\" alt=\"{\"en\":\"Pharmacies in Turkey for UK Travellers: How to Get Common Medicines (Simple, Calm Guide)\",\"tr\":\"Türkiye''de Eczaneler ve İlaç Temini (TR Pasif)\"} - Image 5\" class=\"w-full h-auto rounded-xl shadow-lg\" loading=\"lazy\" onError=\"this.onerror=null;this.src=''/images/articles/turkey_holiday_generic_1767986408887.jpg'';\" />\n</figure>\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<ul>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>Save your accommodation address as text + screenshot</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>Save: “112 — Turkey Emergency”</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>Learn the two key words: eczane (pharmacy) and nöbetçi eczane (on-duty pharmacy)</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>If you’re in a big city, bookmark a local on-duty pharmacy list (example: Istanbul)</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>Put a small “medical note” in your phone (allergies, meds, conditions)</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n</ul>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<p><strong>UK-friendly tip:</strong> This is a 5-minute job that makes your whole trip feel calmer.</p>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<h2>13) Common mistakes UK travellers make (and the easy fixes)</h2>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<p><strong>Mistake 1:</strong> Waiting until Sunday night to figure it out\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<br><strong>Fix:</strong> know the “nöbetçi eczane” concept early.</p>\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<p><strong>Mistake 2:</strong> Bringing a UK prescription and assuming it works\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<br><strong>Fix:</strong> UK prescriptions aren’t accepted as prescriptions in Turkish pharmacies.</p>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<p><strong>Mistake 3:</strong> Asking for “antibiotics” directly\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<br><strong>Fix:</strong> antibiotics need a prescription; ask the pharmacist what’s possible without one, and what the next step is if you need a doctor.</p>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<p><strong>Mistake 4:</strong> Not keeping proof for regular medicines\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<br><strong>Fix:</strong> keep packaging + prescription/doctor letter (digital copy is fine).</p>\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<h2>14) Copy-paste questions to ask a pharmacist (fast clarity)</h2>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<ul>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>“Is this prescription-only in Turkey?”</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>“What is the simplest option for relief without a prescription?”</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>“If I do need a prescription, what is the quickest way to get one locally?”</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>“Can you write down the product name and directions in English?”</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>“Are there any interactions with my current medication?” (show label/photo)</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>“Is there a milder option if I’m sensitive to strong medicines?”</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n</ul>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<p><strong>Simple rule:</strong> The goal is clarity, not speed.</p>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<h2>FAQ: Pharmacies in Turkey for UK travellers</h2>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<h3>What is a pharmacy called in Turkey?</h3>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<p>A pharmacy is called an eczane. After hours, look for a nöbetçi eczane (on-duty pharmacy).</p>\n<figure class=\"my-8\">\n<img src=\"/images/articles/water-bottle-pills-stay-healthy-1767987110935.jpg\" alt=\"{\"en\":\"Pharmacies in Turkey for UK Travellers: How to Get Common Medicines (Simple, Calm Guide)\",\"tr\":\"Türkiye''de Eczaneler ve İlaç Temini (TR Pasif)\"} - Image 6\" class=\"w-full h-auto rounded-xl shadow-lg\" loading=\"lazy\" onError=\"this.onerror=null;this.src=''/images/articles/turkey_holiday_generic_1767986408887.jpg'';\" />\n</figure>\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<h3>Are pharmacies open on Sundays in Turkey?</h3>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<p>Most standard pharmacies close on Sundays, but the on-duty system means certain pharmacies remain open. The easiest method is to search for “nöbetçi eczane” or use a local chamber list (for example, Istanbul’s chamber list).</p>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<h3>What are typical opening hours?</h3>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<p>Hours vary by province, but as a practical reference, Istanbul’s pharmacists’ chamber has published pharmacy hours as 09:00–19:00 in the cited notice.</p>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<h3>Can I use my UK prescription in a Turkish pharmacy?</h3>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<p>The UK Foreign Office states that British prescriptions are not accepted in pharmacies in Turkey. If a medicine needs a prescription in Turkey, you’ll need a Turkish prescription for an equivalent medicine.</p>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<h3>Can I buy antibiotics over the counter in Turkey?</h3>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<p>No — pharmacies are not allowed to dispense antibiotics without a doctor’s prescription in Turkey.</p>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<h3>What should I do in an emergency?</h3>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<p>Call 112 for emergency services in Turkey.</p>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<h3>What should I carry if I travel with regular medication?</h3>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<p>Travel health guidance commonly recommends carrying proof your medicine is prescribed to you (prescription copy and/or a doctor letter), and keeping medicines in original packaging.</p>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\",\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"tr\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"<p>Bu içerik sadece İngilizce dilinde yayındadır.</p>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"}</p>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\",\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"tr\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"<p>Content available in English only.</p>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"}</p>\\\\\\\",\\\\\\\"tr\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\"<p>Content available in English only.</p>\\\\\\\"}</p>\\\",\\\"tr\\\":\\\"<p>Content available in English only.</p>\\\"}</p>\",\"tr\":\"<p>Content available in English only.</p>\"}</p>","tr":"<p>Content available in English only.</p>"}'::jsonb, 
    cover_image_url = '/images/articles/eczane-pharmacy-sign-turkey-street-1767987110935.jpg',
    updated_at = NOW()
WHERE slug = 'pharmacies-in-turkey-for-uk-travellers';

UPDATE articles 
SET content = '{"en":"{\"en\":\"{\\\"en\\\":\\\"{\\\\\\\"en\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\"{\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"en\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"{\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"en\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<p><strong>Quick answer:</strong> For most UK travellers, a <strong>private transfer</strong> is the “sweet spot” for value: it costs only slightly more than a shared shuttle (for a family/group) but saves you 1–2 hours of drop-off loops. Shared shuttles are cheap but slow. Taxis are fine for short hops but can be variable on price. Renting a car just for the airport run is rarely worth the paperwork.</p>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<h2>The 4 main options for UK travellers (ranked by “sanity score”)</h2>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<h3>1) Private Transfer (The UK Favourite)</h3>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<p>You book in advance, the driver waits with a sign (usually your name), and you go straight to your hotel.</p>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<ul>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n  <li><strong>Pros:</strong> Zero waiting, fixed price (£), door-to-door, air-con, often free child seats.</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n  <li><strong>Cons:</strong> You must book before you fly.</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n  <li><strong>Sanity Score:</strong> 10/10</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n</ul>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<h3>2) Shared Shuttle (The Budget Choice)</h3>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<p>You book a seat on a bus. You wait for other flights to land. You stop at 4–8 other hotels before yours.</p>\n<figure class=\"my-8\">\n<img src=\"/images/articles/private-transfer-van-interior-luxury-1767986408887.jpg\" alt=\"{\"en\":\"Resort Transfers in Turkey: Reliable Options and What to Avoid (UK-Friendly Guide)\",\"tr\":\"Türkiye Otel Transfer Rehberi (TR Pasif)\"} - Image 2\" class=\"w-full h-auto rounded-xl shadow-lg\" loading=\"lazy\" onError=\"this.onerror=null;this.src=''/images/articles/turkey_holiday_generic_1767986408887.jpg'';\" />\n</figure>\\n\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<ul>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n  <li><strong>Pros:</strong> Cheap for solo travellers or couples.</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n  <li><strong>Cons:</strong> Can add 1–2 hours to your journey. “First on the bus” often means “last off”.</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n  <li><strong>Sanity Score:</strong> 6/10 (good for price, bad for time)</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n</ul>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<h3>3) Airport Taxi (The \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"I Forgot to Book\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" Option)</h3>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<p>Yellow taxis are available 24/7 at ranks. They use meters (usually).</p>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<ul>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n  <li><strong>Pros:</strong> No pre-booking needed.</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n  <li><strong>Cons:</strong> Price varies by traffic. Not all have child seats. Variable vehicle quality.</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n  <li><strong>Sanity Score:</strong> 7/10</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n</ul>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<h3>4) Hotel Transfer (The \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"Easy but Pricey\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" Option)</h3>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<p>You ask your hotel to arrange it.</p>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<ul>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n  <li><strong>Pros:</strong> If it goes wrong, the hotel fixes it.</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n  <li><strong>Cons:</strong> Often 20–30% more expensive than booking a direct transfer company yourself.</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n  <li><strong>Sanity Score:</strong> 9/10 (you pay for the ease)</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n</ul>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<h2>Transfer time reality check (don''t underestimate distances)</h2>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<p>Turkey’s coast is huge. “Antalya Airport” transfers cover a massive area.</p>\n<figure class=\"my-8\">\n<img src=\"/images/articles/airport-exit-driver-sign-waiting-1767986408887.jpg\" alt=\"{\"en\":\"Resort Transfers in Turkey: Reliable Options and What to Avoid (UK-Friendly Guide)\",\"tr\":\"Türkiye Otel Transfer Rehberi (TR Pasif)\"} - Image 3\" class=\"w-full h-auto rounded-xl shadow-lg\" loading=\"lazy\" onError=\"this.onerror=null;this.src=''/images/articles/turkey_holiday_generic_1767986408887.jpg'';\" />\n</figure>\\n\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<ul>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n  <li><strong>Antalya Airport to Lara Beach:</strong> 20–30 mins</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n  <li><strong>Antalya Airport to Belek:</strong> 30–45 mins</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n  <li><strong>Antalya Airport to Side:</strong> 60–75 mins</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n  <li><strong>Antalya Airport to Alanya:</strong> 2 hours+ (This is the one that catches people out!)</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n</ul>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<p><strong>Dalaman Airport:</strong>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<ul>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n  <li><strong>To Marmaris:</strong> 90 mins</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n  <li><strong>To Fethiye/Ölüdeniz:</strong> 60 mins</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n</ul>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<p><strong>Bodrum Airport:</strong>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<ul>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n  <li><strong>To Bodrum Town:</strong> 40 mins</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n</ul>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<h2>How to spot reliable companies (UK-friendly checklist)</h2>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<p>Don''t just pick the cheapest Google ad.</p>\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<ul>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n  <li><strong>Do they have a 24/7 WhatsApp number?</strong> (Essential if your flight is delayed).</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n  <li><strong>Do they ask for your flight number?</strong> (So they track delays).</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n  <li><strong>Do they offer \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"pay on arrival\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" or \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"free cancellation\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"?</strong> (Avoids risk if plans change).</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n  <li><strong>Are child seats free/guaranteed?</strong> (Good companies always offer this).</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n</ul>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<h2>The \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"Airport Stress\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" Trap (and how to avoid it)</h2>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<p>The biggest stress is landing, feeling the heat, wrangling tired kids/bags, and <em>then</em> trying to negotiate transport.</p>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<p><strong>Rule:</strong> If you are travelling with kids or landing after 9 pm, <strong>pre-book a private transfer</strong>. The extra £20 is worth avoiding the argument at the taxi rank.</p>\n<figure class=\"my-8\">\n<img src=\"/images/articles/shuttle-bus-sharing-tourists-1767986408887.jpg\" alt=\"{\"en\":\"Resort Transfers in Turkey: Reliable Options and What to Avoid (UK-Friendly Guide)\",\"tr\":\"Türkiye Otel Transfer Rehberi (TR Pasif)\"} - Image 4\" class=\"w-full h-auto rounded-xl shadow-lg\" loading=\"lazy\" onError=\"this.onerror=null;this.src=''/images/articles/turkey_holiday_generic_1767986408887.jpg'';\" />\n</figure>\\n\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<h2>FAQ: UK Traveller Transfers</h2>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<h3>Do transfer drivers speak English?</h3>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<p>Usually basic \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"transport English\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\". But they have WhatsApp and Google Translate. It’s rarely an issue.</p>\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<h3>Do I tip the transfer driver?</h3>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<p>It''s polite but not mandatory. 50–100 TL (or £2–£3) is appreciated for help with bags.</p>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<h3>What if my flight is delayed?</h3>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<p>If you gave your flight number, they track it. If it''s a huge delay (4+ hours), message them on WhatsApp before you fly.</p>\n<figure class=\"my-8\">\n<img src=\"/images/articles/taxi-rank-airport-queue-1767986408887.jpg\" alt=\"{\"en\":\"Resort Transfers in Turkey: Reliable Options and What to Avoid (UK-Friendly Guide)\",\"tr\":\"Türkiye Otel Transfer Rehberi (TR Pasif)\"} - Image 5\" class=\"w-full h-auto rounded-xl shadow-lg\" loading=\"lazy\" onError=\"this.onerror=null;this.src=''/images/articles/turkey_holiday_generic_1767986408887.jpg'';\" />\n</figure>\\n\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<h3>Can I use Uber?</h3>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<p>Uber exists in Istanbul (calls yellow taxis) and some coastal spots, but it''s not reliable for long <em>airport-to-resort</em> journeys. Stick to pre-booked transfers.</p>\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\",\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"tr\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"<p>Bu içerik sadece İngilizce dilinde yayındadır.</p>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"}</p>\n<figure class=\"my-8\">\n<img src=\"/images/articles/family-loading-luggage-car-boot-1767986408887.jpg\" alt=\"{\"en\":\"Resort Transfers in Turkey: Reliable Options and What to Avoid (UK-Friendly Guide)\",\"tr\":\"Türkiye Otel Transfer Rehberi (TR Pasif)\"} - Image 6\" class=\"w-full h-auto rounded-xl shadow-lg\" loading=\"lazy\" onError=\"this.onerror=null;this.src=''/images/articles/turkey_holiday_generic_1767986408887.jpg'';\" />\n</figure>\\n\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\",\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"tr\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"<p>Content available in English only.</p>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"}</p>\\\\\\\",\\\\\\\"tr\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\"<p>Content available in English only.</p>\\\\\\\"}</p>\\\",\\\"tr\\\":\\\"<p>Content available in English only.</p>\\\"}</p>\",\"tr\":\"<p>Content available in English only.</p>\"}</p>","tr":"<p>Content available in English only.</p>"}'::jsonb, 
    cover_image_url = '/images/articles/resort_transfers_map_app_1770577751586.png',
    updated_at = NOW()
WHERE slug = 'turkey-resort-transfers-guide';

UPDATE articles 
SET content = '{"en":"{\"en\":\"{\\\"en\\\":\\\"{\\\\\\\"en\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\"{\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"en\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"{\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"en\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<p><strong>Quick answer:</strong> Most UK travellers have a great time in Turkey with no issues — and the easiest way to keep it that way is to follow three “comfort habits”: (1) hydrate smart, (2) keep food choices simple on day 1, and (3) respect the midday heat. You don’t need fear-based rules. You need a calm routine that protects your energy so the trip feels premium.</p>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<p>This guide is about comfort, not worry.</p>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<h2>The UK traveller mindset that works best in Turkey</h2>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<p>Turkey holidays can be more active than you think: hotter weather, more walking, later dinners, and a different daily rhythm. If you treat “wellbeing” as part of your itinerary, you’ll enjoy more.</p>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<p><strong>Simple rule:</strong> Your goal is not “avoid everything” — your goal is “stay energised”.</p>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<p><strong>UK-friendly tip:</strong> The best Turkey holidays have a soft midday: shade, water, slow lunch, then you come alive again late afternoon/evening.</p>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<h2>Part 1 — Water: what to drink (without overthinking)</h2>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<p>The real question isn’t “Is the water safe?”</p>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<p>The useful question is: what will keep your stomach comfortable on holiday?</p>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<p>Many travellers choose to drink:</p>\n<figure class=\"my-8\">\n<img src=\"/images/articles/fresh-fruit-market-stall-turkey-1767986408887.jpg\" alt=\"{\"en\":\"Staying Well in Turkey: Food, Water & Heat Comfort Tips for UK Travellers (No-Panic Guide)\",\"tr\":\"Türkiye''de Sağlıklı Kalmak: Su, Yemek ve Sıcaklık İpuçları (TR Pasif)\"} - Image 2\" class=\"w-full h-auto rounded-xl shadow-lg\" loading=\"lazy\" onError=\"this.onerror=null;this.src=''/images/articles/turkey_holiday_generic_1767986408887.jpg'';\" />\n</figure>\\n\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<ul>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>sealed bottled water for day-to-day hydration</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>hot drinks (tea/coffee) as normal</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>sealed soft drinks and canned drinks</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>ice when they’re confident in the venue (especially reputable, busy places)</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n</ul>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<p><strong>Simple rule:</strong> If you want the calmest trip, make bottled water your default.</p>\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<h3>A simple approach that works in practice</h3>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<p><strong>Day 1–2: stick to sealed bottled water for drinking</strong>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<ul>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>Brush teeth: many travellers still use tap water with no problems, but if you want zero mental load, use bottled water the first couple of days too</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>If you’re unsure about ice: skip it for a day or two, then decide based on comfort</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n</ul>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<p><strong>UK-friendly tip:</strong> Don’t let “water decisions” become your holiday. Pick a default (bottled) and move on.</p>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<h3>Hydration that actually helps (not just “drink more”)</h3>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<p>When it’s hot, you lose more fluid and salts through sweat.</p>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<p>Try this rhythm:</p>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<ul>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>Morning: 1–2 glasses before you head out</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>Midday: steady sips + something salty/food</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>Late afternoon: one “reset” drink before dinner</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>Evening: hydrate, but don’t overdo it right before bed</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n</ul>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<p><strong>Simple rule:</strong> Hydration works best when you drink regularly, not in one big hit.</p>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<h2>Part 2 — Heat & sun: how to stay comfortable (and still enjoy summer)</h2>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<h3>Why heat “hits” UK travellers</h3>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<p>If you live in the UK most of the year, Turkey’s summer sun can feel like a different category — not because it’s scary, but because your body isn’t used to it.</p>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<p>Common “holiday fatigue” triggers:</p>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<ul>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>too much sun between 12:00–16:00</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>not enough water + salts</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>long walks without shade breaks</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>alcohol + sun combo</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>pushing through instead of resting</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n</ul>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<p><strong>Simple rule:</strong> The midday sun is not the time to prove anything.</p>\n<figure class=\"my-8\">\n<img src=\"/images/articles/water-bottle-beach-sun-hat-1767987110935.jpg\" alt=\"{\"en\":\"Staying Well in Turkey: Food, Water & Heat Comfort Tips for UK Travellers (No-Panic Guide)\",\"tr\":\"Türkiye''de Sağlıklı Kalmak: Su, Yemek ve Sıcaklık İpuçları (TR Pasif)\"} - Image 3\" class=\"w-full h-auto rounded-xl shadow-lg\" loading=\"lazy\" onError=\"this.onerror=null;this.src=''/images/articles/turkey_holiday_generic_1767986408887.jpg'';\" />\n</figure>\\n\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<h3>The Turkey midday plan (the one that makes holidays feel luxury)</h3>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<p>This is the simplest high-impact routine:</p>\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<ul>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>Morning: beach/pool/walks/exploring</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>Midday: shade + lunch + slow time + nap/quiet</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>Late afternoon: beach/pool again</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>Evening: dinner + strolling + enjoying the vibe</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n</ul>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<p><strong>UK-friendly tip:</strong> If you copy local rhythm, you’ll feel better fast. Turkey does evenings brilliantly — save your energy for them.</p>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<h3>Heat comfort checklist (quick wins)</h3>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<ul>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>Wear breathable fabrics</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>Use a hat/cap</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>Keep sunscreen where you can reapply (bag, not suitcase)</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>Choose shade before you feel bad</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>If you feel drained: cool shower + water + salty snack</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n</ul>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<p><strong>Simple rule:</strong> Prevention beats recovery.</p>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<h3>Sun protection that’s realistic (not perfectionist)</h3>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<p>You don’t need to be obsessed — you need to be consistent.</p>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<ul>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>Apply sunscreen before you go out</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>Reapply after swimming/sweating</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>Don’t forget ears, neck, tops of feet</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n</ul>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<p><strong>UK-friendly tip:</strong> Most “sun problems” happen on day 1–2 because people underestimate it. Treat the first two days as your “adaptation period”.</p>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<h2>Part 3 — Food: how to eat well and keep your stomach calm</h2>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<h3>Turkey is a food country — enjoy it</h3>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<p>This guide isn’t here to make you nervous. Turkish food culture is a highlight. The trick is to be smart on timing, not restrictive.</p>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<p><strong>Simple rule:</strong> Eat confidently — just don’t shock your system on day 1.</p>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<h3>Day 1 food strategy (works for most UK travellers)</h3>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<p>After a flight + heat + schedule change, your body likes simple food.</p>\n<figure class=\"my-8\">\n<img src=\"/images/articles/grilled-vegetables-healthy-meal-1767986408887.jpg\" alt=\"{\"en\":\"Staying Well in Turkey: Food, Water & Heat Comfort Tips for UK Travellers (No-Panic Guide)\",\"tr\":\"Türkiye''de Sağlıklı Kalmak: Su, Yemek ve Sıcaklık İpuçları (TR Pasif)\"} - Image 4\" class=\"w-full h-auto rounded-xl shadow-lg\" loading=\"lazy\" onError=\"this.onerror=null;this.src=''/images/articles/turkey_holiday_generic_1767986408887.jpg'';\" />\n</figure>\\n\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<p>Good Day 1 choices:</p>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<ul>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>grilled items</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>rice/potatoes/bread</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>yoghurt-based foods if you tolerate dairy</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>soups</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>fruit you can peel</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>cooked vegetables</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n</ul>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<p><strong>UK-friendly tip:</strong> If you’re going all-inclusive, don’t try “everything” at once on day 1. Try a few things, then expand.</p>\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<p>Related: <a href=\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"/guide/all-inclusive-in-turkey-explained-uk-guide\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\">All-Inclusive: What’s Included</a>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\nRelated: <a href=\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"/guide/hidden-costs-turkey-resorts\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\">Hidden Costs in Turkey Resorts</a>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<h3>Street food: enjoy it the smart way</h3>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<p>Street food can be amazing. The comfort method is:</p>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<ul>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>choose places with high turnover (busy is good)</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>prefer freshly cooked hot food</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>avoid anything that’s been sitting in heat for ages</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n</ul>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<p><strong>Simple rule:</strong> Busy + fresh + hot = usually your best bet.</p>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<h3>Buffets (all-inclusive): how to do it like a pro</h3>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<p>Buffets are convenient and often great — and there’s an easy way to make them feel better.</p>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<ul>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>Choose food that’s clearly hot and freshly replenished</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>Avoid “mixing everything” on one plate</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>If you try something new, try a small portion first</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>If you’re sensitive, keep breakfast simple and experiment more at dinner</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n</ul>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<p><strong>UK-friendly tip:</strong> Your stomach likes routine. If breakfast is the same most days, the rest of the day is easier.</p>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<h2>Part 4 — The “holiday stomach” reality (calm, practical)</h2>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<p>Sometimes travellers feel off for totally non-dramatic reasons:</p>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<ul>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>heat + dehydration</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>travel fatigue</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>irregular meals</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>more oil/spice than usual</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>alcohol + sun</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n</ul>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<p><strong>Simple rule:</strong> If you feel off, reset your basics first: water + bland food + rest.</p>\n<figure class=\"my-8\">\n<img src=\"/images/articles/tourist-drinking-tea-cafe-shade-1767986640560.jpg\" alt=\"{\"en\":\"Staying Well in Turkey: Food, Water & Heat Comfort Tips for UK Travellers (No-Panic Guide)\",\"tr\":\"Türkiye''de Sağlıklı Kalmak: Su, Yemek ve Sıcaklık İpuçları (TR Pasif)\"} - Image 5\" class=\"w-full h-auto rounded-xl shadow-lg\" loading=\"lazy\" onError=\"this.onerror=null;this.src=''/images/articles/turkey_holiday_generic_1767986408887.jpg'';\" />\n</figure>\\n\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<h3>The 24-hour reset plan (non-medical, comfort-focused)</h3>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<p>If you feel unsettled:</p>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<ul>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>drink steadily (don’t chug)</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>eat simple foods</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>avoid heavy alcohol</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>take a quiet midday break</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>sleep earlier</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n</ul>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<p>If you’re worried or symptoms are severe/worsening, get professional help promptly.</p>\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<p><strong>Emergency support reminder:</strong> 112 is the main emergency number in Turkey.</p>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<h2>Part 5 — Families: how to keep kids happy in Turkey heat</h2>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<p>Kids usually do great in Turkey — as long as you protect the basics.</p>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<h3>The family comfort priorities</h3>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<ul>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>shade access</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>regular water breaks</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>snack rhythm</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>midday downtime</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>early nights if needed</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n</ul>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<p><strong>Simple rule:</strong> Kids don’t “push through heat” well. Build shade into the day.</p>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<p>Family guide: <a href=\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"/guide/all-inclusive-family-checklist\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\">Family All-Inclusive Checklist</a>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<h3>Easy parent trick: “water + salt + shade”</h3>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<p>If your child looks wiped:</p>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<ul>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>water</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>something salty (food/snack)</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>cool down in shade/air-con</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n</ul>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<p><strong>UK-friendly tip:</strong> Keep a small “heat kit” in your bag: wipes, a hat, and a spare top.</p>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<h2>Part 6 — What to pack for comfort (UK-friendly mini list)</h2>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<p>This is not a massive packing list — just the items that make a big difference.</p>\n<figure class=\"my-8\">\n<img src=\"/images/articles/sunscreen-application-poolside-1767987110935.jpg\" alt=\"{\"en\":\"Staying Well in Turkey: Food, Water & Heat Comfort Tips for UK Travellers (No-Panic Guide)\",\"tr\":\"Türkiye''de Sağlıklı Kalmak: Su, Yemek ve Sıcaklık İpuçları (TR Pasif)\"} - Image 6\" class=\"w-full h-auto rounded-xl shadow-lg\" loading=\"lazy\" onError=\"this.onerror=null;this.src=''/images/articles/turkey_holiday_generic_1767986408887.jpg'';\" />\n</figure>\\n\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<h3>Heat comfort essentials</h3>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<ul>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>hat/cap</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>sunglasses</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>sunscreen</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>lightweight layer for evenings/air-con</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>rehydration support (or plan to buy locally)</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n</ul>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<h3>Stomach comfort essentials</h3>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<ul>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>a couple of “safe snacks” for day 1 (plain biscuits, etc.)</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>basic plasters and antiseptic wipes</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>any regular medication in original packaging</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n</ul>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<p><strong>UK-friendly tip:</strong> Don’t pack a pharmacy. Pack a routine.</p>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<p>If you need medicines while there, pharmacies (“eczane”) are common — and there’s an on-duty system outside normal hours in many areas. (Example info via Istanbul’s pharmacists’ chamber communications.)</p>\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<h2>Part 7 — Copy-paste questions (save these)</h2>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<p>Use these in resorts, restaurants, or with guides:</p>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<ul>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>“What’s your most popular freshly cooked dish?”</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>“Which dishes are mild (not spicy)?”</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>“Is this served fresh today?”</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>“Do you have bottled water available?”</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>“We’re travelling with kids — what’s the best shaded time for activities?”</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>“Is there a quiet, shaded area we can use midday?”</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n</ul>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<p><strong>Simple rule:</strong> Asking one simple question prevents a lot of discomfort.</p>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<h2>Part 8 — The “No-Panic Comfort Checklist” (save this)</h2>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<h3>Every morning</h3>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<ul>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>water before leaving the room ✅</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>sunscreen before the sun “feels strong” ✅</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>plan shade for midday ✅</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n</ul>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<h3>Day 1–2</h3>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<ul>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>keep food simple ✅</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>bottled water as default ✅</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>don’t overdo alcohol in the sun ✅</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n</ul>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<h3>If you feel off</h3>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<ul>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>hydration + salty food ✅</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>rest in shade/air-con ✅</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<li>simple meals ✅</li>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n</ul>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<p><strong>UK-friendly tip:</strong> If you do nothing else, do the morning water + midday shade. It’s the biggest win.</p>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<h2>FAQ: Food, water & heat comfort in Turkey (UK travellers)</h2>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<h3>Should UK travellers drink bottled water in Turkey?</h3>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<p>Many UK travellers choose bottled water as a simple comfort default because it removes guesswork and helps avoid stomach upset during the first days of travel. It’s a low-effort habit that often makes the trip feel smoother.</p>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<h3>Is ice okay?</h3>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<p>In many reputable places, ice is commonly used. If you want the calmest approach, skip ice for the first day or two and then decide based on your comfort and the venue.</p>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<h3>What’s the best way to avoid feeling wiped out in the heat?</h3>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<p>Use the local rhythm: active morning, shaded midday break, then late afternoon and evening enjoyment. Hydrate steadily and don’t treat midday sun like an endurance test.</p>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<h3>What’s the best Day 1 food plan?</h3>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<p>Simple, familiar food (grilled items, rice/potatoes, soups, fruit you can peel) and smaller portions. Let your body settle, then explore more.</p>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<h3>Are buffets risky?</h3>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<p>Buffets can be absolutely fine. The comfort method is to choose food that’s clearly hot and fresh, avoid mixing too many new items at once, and keep breakfast simple.</p>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<h3>What should I do if someone in our group feels unwell?</h3>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n<p>Start with basic comfort steps (rest, hydration, simple food). If symptoms are severe, worsening, or you’re concerned, seek professional help. For emergencies, Turkey’s main emergency number is 112.</p>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\",\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"tr\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"<p>Bu içerik sadece İngilizce dilinde yayındadır.</p>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"}</p>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\",\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"tr\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"<p>Content available in English only.</p>\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"}</p>\\\\\\\",\\\\\\\"tr\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\"<p>Content available in English only.</p>\\\\\\\"}</p>\\\",\\\"tr\\\":\\\"<p>Content available in English only.</p>\\\"}</p>\",\"tr\":\"<p>Content available in English only.</p>\"}</p>","tr":"<p>Content available in English only.</p>"}'::jsonb, 
